  billReadingTips={[
    "HESCO and SEPCO are separate companies. If your bill heading says HESCO, you are in lower Sindh. If it says SEPCO, visit our SEPCO bill page.",
    "Tharparkar consumers: HESCO covers all of Tharparkar district. In the remote desert areas of Mithi and Nagarparkar, paper bill delivery is often unreliable — always check your bill online to know your due date.",
    "Hyderabad industrial consumers in SITE and Kotri industrial areas: check your Maximum Demand (MD) reading on the bill. Industrial MD charges apply when peak demand exceeds sanctioned load.",
    "Monsoon season (July to September) in interior Sindh often causes billing disruptions due to flooding. HESCO may issue estimated bills during this period. Request actual readings once flood conditions clear.",
    "Badin and Thatta coastal consumers: sea air causes rapid meter corrosion. Request free meter inspection every 2 years — corroded meters often show inflated readings.",
  ]}
  savingTips={[
    "Hyderabad summers exceed 44°C. Managing AC usage is the single biggest opportunity to save on HESCO bills. Use inverter ACs, set to 26°C, and operate fans simultaneously.",
    "Interior Sindh's rural consumers: agricultural tube wells running on HESCO electricity should use timers to operate during off-peak morning hours (6 AM to 12 PM).",
    "Tharparkar's extraordinary solar potential: annual solar irradiance in Tharparkar is among the highest in Pakistan. HESCO net metering makes solar panels extremely cost-effective here.",
    "Avoid electric heaters in Sindh winters. Even in January, interior Sindh temperatures rarely fall below 8°C — warm clothing and heavy blankets eliminate the need for electric heating entirely.",
    "Check if paper bills are arriving regularly. In remote Badin, Thatta, and Tharparkar areas, billing errors go undetected for months because consumers do not see the bill. Use our tool monthly.",
  ]}
